instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "A digital twin is structured as a framework that integrates three core components: data ingestion, modelling, and algorithms. Data is collected from the physical twin via sensors over continuous operational periods and fed into the system for real‑time update. Modelling comprises physical, cyber‑physical, and environmental knowledge bases; these models are continuously refined through calibration algorithms that adjust parameters based on incoming sensor data. The algorithmic layer includes fault detectors, supervisory controllers, state estimators, and optimisers that process the calibrated models and data to generate new insights and actionable outputs. The output from algorithms fuels monitors that evaluate safety and performance; when violations are detected, humans or autonomous decision‑making modules can issue corrective actions to the physical twin. This orchestrated interaction between data, model calibration, monitoring, and control constitutes the overall digital‑twin constellation."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "Digital Twin lifecycle begins with the creation of CAD or dynamic simulation models of the physical system; during deployment the models are integrated with real‑time sensor data from the Physical Twin, followed by continuous calibration and monitoring that update model parameters and evaluate safety/optimisation; governance is achieved by periodic audit of model–data consistency and traceable configuration changes."
]
